liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The health ministry in the Gaza Strip says an Israeli air strike hit a building in the Al Shifa hospital complex, killing one Palestinian, but Israel has denied it targeted the hospital. Gaza's health ministry spokesman said 170 patients and hundreds of displaced Palestinians were in the hospital building at the time. He said several Palestinians were wounded in the strike. But an Israeli military spokesperson, when asked about the claim, said: "There was no IDF (Israel Defense Forces) strike on the Shifa hospital." Earlier, Al Jazeera TV and Hamas-affiliated Al Aqsa radio said Israeli forces had targeted a solar panel system at the hospital complex. Chief IDF spokesperson Rear Admiral Daniel Hagari, asked about those reports during a briefing with reporters, said: "We didn't attack, to the best of my knowledge, solar panels in the Shifa hospital." Israel's military has previously presented alleged evidence showing the hospitals are used by Hamas as bases of operation. Claims that cannot be independently verified. Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israel denies hospital strike which Gaza health ministry says killed one

He said several Palestinians were wounded in the strike.

Claims that cannot be independently verified.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Labor MP Bill Shorten has called the federal Greens "opportunists" after they walked out of the Senate in support of Palestinians yesterday. During Senate Question Time, senator Mehreen Faruqi declared the Greens brought the "people's protest" into parliament after leading her colleagues in a walkout. Senator Janet Rice raised a printed page showing the Palestinian flag as they walked out. Mr Shorten this morning said no one thinks this move helps. "I don't think the Greens walking out helps a single soul anywhere. I think that is just political grand standing. I don't know how that helps," he said "I think that the Government has the right line of length. We want to make sure that we are supporting the humanitarian pause. "We want to see relief get through to innocent Palestinian civilians. "But you know, with the Greens … they don't walk out over Hamas. So I think that these guys are opportunists." He said the Australian government's messaging on the issue is right. "This most recent shocking conflict was triggered by Hamas crossing the borders into Israel," he said. "I think the government has made its position clear that Israel has a right to defend itself. "We also want to make sure that, to the extent that it is possible, the rules of war are followed. "That means these civilians, these Palestinian civilians, it's not their fault. It's shameful. What we're seeing is very difficult too." You can read more about what transpired yesterday here:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Bill Shorten: Greens walkout 'political grand standing'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: As much as Spurs might want to argue about the Romero red card, there was a challenge earlier in the match that I personally found far more egregious. Destiny Udogie flew in, two footed to win the ball against Raheem Sterling. He did win the ball. Just. And missed Sterling. Just. But the challenge itself was horrendous and the Spurs fullback is lucky to only be shown a yellow for mine.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Should Destiny Udogie have been sent off?

children.content: As much as Spurs might want to argue about the Romero red card, there was a challenge earlier in the match that I personally found far more egregious.
Destiny Udogie flew in, two footed to win the ball against Raheem Sterling.
He did win the ball. Just. And missed Sterling. Just.
But the challenge itself was horrendous and the Spurs fullback is lucky to only be shown a yellow for mine.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The big talking point was the red card for Cristian Romaro. He was shown the card after a long VAR check after coming through the ball - after winning it - and catching the man on the shin. It was considered reckless and dangerous and a red card. But should he have even been on the pitch in the first place? Earlier in the match he kicked out at Thiago Silva after a solid challenge in the Chelsea half. It was David Beckham vs Diego Simeone-like if you need a reference. It might get lost in the overall washup from that mad first opening 45, but he was probably lucky to still be out there.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Was a red card fair for Romaro?

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: So, we get to the end of an extraordinary half of football. Spurs were rampant early on, but it's all gone wrong in a big way for Ange Postecoglou since then. Cristian Romero has been sent off, the other half of that excellent centre back partnership, Micky van de Ven, has gone off with a hamstring injury and key player James Maddison has gone off injured. But despite all that it's still 1-1, with both teams having goals ruled out by a forensic VAR that is investigating every little incident so far in this game. Two goals, three chalked off, a red card… It's been a wild one - and we're only half way through.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Half time, Spurs 1-1 Chelsea

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market is likely to slip in morning trade, snapping its five-day winning streak. ASX futures were down 0.2%, following a subdued performance on Wall Street overnight. US markets have just finished trading, with the Dow Jones, S & P 500 and Nasdaq Composite rising 0.1%, 0.2% and 0.3% respectively. The main US stock indexes were trading in the red, until they made a final-hour recovery. Last week, the S & P climbed 5.9% and the Nasdaq surged 6.6% (marking their best weeks since November 2022). The Dow jumped 5.1% last week (its biggest weekly gain since October 2022) on hopes the US Federal Reserve is near the end of its rate-hiking cycle.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If there's one lesson our new Reserve Bank governor hasn't gleaned from her predecessor, it is the danger of being overly precise. Michele Bullock has been adamant that taming inflation in a timely matter is a top priority. A fortnight ago, however, she added a dash of precision to the message. The RBA, she said, "would not hesitate" to lift rates again if there was a "material" change to the inflation forecasts. Lo and behold, when the September quarter inflation figures dropped, the numbers were hotter than the RBA's forecasts. That put a question mark over the bank's well-telegraphed plan to gradually bring inflation back to between 2 and 3 per cent by 2025. Many now argue that the material change clause that's been inserted into the dialogue looks to have been triggered and the RBA has little option but to follow through. For more, here's the latest analysis from business editor Ian Verrender :
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Why the Reserve Bank will probably lift interest rates on Melbourne Cup Day even though it doesn't need to

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Ahead of this afternoon's decision by the RBA, here's a quick refresher of where the current cash rate sits. After leaving rates on hold at 4.1% since its June meeting, the cash rate is currently the highest it's been since April 2012. Should the RBA lift interest rates by 0.25 percentage points at 2:30pm AEDT, it would take the cash rate to 4.35%. That would make it the highest rate since November 2011 — which is a whopping 12 years ago, if you can believe it. (I personally can't...) Here's the history of the cash rate since 1990. As you can see, when we look at the data from more than 30 years, the recent rate hikes are incredibly steep compared to past increases.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: What does the current cash rate look like?
